
TY  - JOUR
T1  - Technology Success and Failure in Winner-Take-All Markets: The Impact of Learning Orientation, Timing, and Network Externalities
AU  - Schilling, Melissa A.
Y1  - 2002/04/01
PY  - 2002
DA  - 2002/04/01
N1  - doi: 10.5465/3069353
DO  - 10.5465/3069353
T2  - Academy of Management Journal
JF  - Academy of Management Journal
JO  - AMJ
SP  - 387
EP  - 398
VL  - 45
IS  - 2
PB  - Academy of Management
N2  - In industries characterized by network externalities, a single technology standard often rises to dominance, locking out competing technologies. This research demonstrates that despite ?path dependency,? it is possible to model the technology selection process and predict likely outcomes. This work extends previous work in network externalities by demonstrating that in addition to its ?installed base? and the availability of complementary goods, a firm's learning orientation and timing of entry also play significant roles in its success.
AB  - In industries characterized by network externalities, a single technology standard often rises to dominance, locking out competing technologies. This research demonstrates that despite ?path dependency,? it is possible to model the technology selection process and predict likely outcomes. This work extends previous work in network externalities by demonstrating that in addition to its ?installed base? and the availability of complementary goods, a firm's learning orientation and timing of entry also play significant roles in its success.
SN  - 0001-4273
M3  - doi: 10.5465/3069353
UR  - https://doi.org/10.5465/3069353
Y2  - 2026/04/24
