TY  - JOUR
T1  - A Network Effects Model of Charisma Attributions
AU  - Pastor, Juan-Carlos
AU  - Meindl, James R.
AU  - Mayo, Margarita C.
Y1  - 2002/04/01
PY  - 2002
DA  - 2002/04/01
N1  - doi: 10.5465/3069355
DO  - 10.5465/3069355
T2  - Academy of Management Journal
JF  - Academy of Management Journal
JO  - AMJ
SP  - 410
EP  - 420
VL  - 45
IS  - 2
PB  - Academy of Management
N2  - We propose a network effects model of charisma that specifies the distribution and change of charisma attributions among individuals connected in a social structure. Data from a police organization and a classroom setting were analyzed using social network methods. The results show that social network parameters are significantly associated with the distribution and dispersion of attributions of charisma. Results are discussed in terms of their theoretical significance for understanding the socialized aspects of charisma attributions.
AB  - We propose a network effects model of charisma that specifies the distribution and change of charisma attributions among individuals connected in a social structure. Data from a police organization and a classroom setting were analyzed using social network methods. The results show that social network parameters are significantly associated with the distribution and dispersion of attributions of charisma. Results are discussed in terms of their theoretical significance for understanding the socialized aspects of charisma attributions.
